4.3.2. Scaling with Problem Size
Fig. 5 depicts the performance of the multi-threaded version of Jack on 8 threads for two diÔ¨Äerent step sizes
and three diÔ¨Äerent problem sizes. As the number of particles increases, the scalability of the application improves
because there is more work available for each thread, reducing Ô¨Åxed-cost overhead of the Ô¨Ånal synchronization
and reduction operations. At smaller problem sizes, smaller step sizes also serve to provide more work for each
thread, improving scalability as shown by the .01 mm vs. .1 mm bars.

